🎓 Spendora Student Expense Tracker

✨ What is this project?

Spendora Student Expense Tracker is a modern student finance website that helps users manage money in a clean and simple way. It separates the app into pages like dashboard, transactions, budgets, goals, and analytics so each task stays easy to use.
💡 Why it is useful

Students usually manage allowance, part-time income, hostel fees, food spending, transport, books, and personal expenses. This project makes that easier by turning money tracking into a visual and structured workflow.

🚀 Main Features

- **Dashboard** — See income, expenses, balance, and charts.
- **Transactions** — Add and manage income or expense records.
- **Budgets** — Set monthly category limits.
- **Goals** — Track savings targets.
- **Analytics** — View summary insights and patterns.
- **Theme toggle** — Switch between light and dark mode.
- **Responsive UI** — Works on mobile and desktop.

🗂️ Pages in the Website

| Page | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| Home | Landing and navigation |
| Dashboard | Overview and charts |
| Transactions | Add income and expenses |
| Budgets | Manage monthly limits |
| Goals | Save for targets |
| Analytics | Review spending behavior |

## 📁 Folder Structure

```bash
student-expense-tracker/
├── index.html
├── dashboard.html
├── transactions.html
├── budgets.html
├── goals.html
├── analytics.html
├── css/
└── js/
```

## 🧭 User Flow

1. Open the home page.
2. Add income and expense entries.
3. Set budgets for each category.
4. Create savings goals.
5. Review everything on the dashboard.
6. Study analytics and improve spending habits.

## 🛠️ Tech Stack

- HTML5
- CSS3
- JavaScript
- Chart.js

## 📌 Future Enhancements

- localStorage persistence
- Firebase authentication
- cloud database support
- CSV/PDF export
- reminders and recurring bills
- better visual analytics

## 📝 Resume Line

Spendora Student Expense Tracker is a responsive multi-page finance web app built using HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and Chart.js to help students track income, expenses, budgets, savings goals, and analytics.
